      GameStop report!
   =20
 =20
Yesterday the=C2=A0U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission released a =E2=
=80=9CStaff Report on Equity and Options Market Structure Conditions in Ear=
ly 2021,=E2=80=9D specifically the conditions that allowed GameStop Corp.=
=E2=80=99s stock to go from $17.25 to $325 over the course of January for n=
o particular reason. It would have been cool if the SEC had, uh, found a re=
ason. If the report was like =E2=80=9Cactually we looked deep into the stoc=
k exchange=E2=80=99s computers and found that they accidentally shifted a d=
ecimal point one spot to the right, that was supposed to be $32.50, oops,=
=E2=80=9D that would have been an interesting result.Or at the time this wa=
s all happening, there were a lot of theories about =E2=80=9Cshort squeezes=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgamma squeezes=E2=80=9D and nefarious hedge funds do=
ing evil things to manipulate=C2=A0the stock. If the SEC had said =E2=80=9C=
it was gamma, just so much gamma,=E2=80=9D that would have added to our und=
erstanding of the world. Or if it had said =E2=80=9Cactually some big hedge=
 funds=C2=A0were hugely long GameStop and manipulated the price up behind t=
he scenes by doing wash trades with their=C2=A0cronies,=E2=80=9D that would=
 have been really cool and fun.=C2=A0But instead the SEC report =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0look,=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s not a=C2=A0bad=C2=A0report. If the GameStop s=
aga got you interested in market structure, if you read a few GameStop arti=
cles and started thinking things like =E2=80=9Cwait how can more than 100% =
of the stock be sold short=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy would Citadel Securitie=
s pay Robinhood to trade with=C2=A0its customers=E2=80=99 orders=E2=80=9D o=
r =E2=80=9Cwhat is a gamma squeeze,=E2=80=9D then the SEC report is a crisp=
, sober, sensible, useful and readable explainer. It=E2=80=99s fine! But if=
 you spent the week of GameStop immersed in GameStop then there is nothing =
all that new here. It=E2=80=99s a little boring. =E2=80=9CMany observers an=
ticipated much more,=E2=80=9D says DealBook. GameStop was so big, and so we=
ird! This one stock going up a lot dominated the national news for like a w=
eek. It cries out for a correspondingly big and weird explanation. But, nah=
. People just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0liked the stock?So: Did GameStop rocket up bec=
ause of a short squeeze?[1] Yes, a bit,=C2=A0the SEC says, but in fact the =
short sellers who threw in the towel and bought in their GameStop shorts we=
re only a small percentage of volume, and they mostly did so=C2=A0early=C2=
=A0in GameStop=E2=80=99s big run in the last week of January:Staff observed=
 that during some discrete periods, GME had sharp price increases concurren=
tly with known major short sellers covering their short positions after inc=
urring significant losses. During these times, short sellers covering their=
 positions likely contributed to increases in GME=E2=80=99s price.=C2=A0For=
 example, staff observed that=C2=A0particularly during the earlier rise fro=
m January 22 to 27 the price of GME rose as the short interest decreased. S=
taff also observed discrete periods of sharp price increases during which a=
ccounts held by firms known to the staff to be covering short interest in G=
ME were actively buying large volumes of GME shares, in some cases accounti=
ng for very significant portions of the net buying pressure during a period=
. Figure 6 shows that buy volume in GME, including buy volume from particip=
ants identified as having large short positions, increased significantly be=
ginning around January 22 and remained high for several days, corresponding=
 to the beginning of the most dramatic phase of the run-up in GME=E2=80=99s=
 price.Figure 6 shows that the run-up in GME stock price coincided with buy=
ing by those with short positions. However, it also shows that such buying =
was a small fraction of overall buy volume, and that GME share prices conti=
nued to be high after the direct effects of covering short positions would =
have waned. The underlying motivation of such buy volume cannot be determin=
ed; perhaps it was motivated by the desire to maintain a short squeeze. Whe=
ther driven by a desire to squeeze short sellers and thus to profit from th=
e resultant rise in price, or by belief in the fundamentals of GameStop, it=
 was the positive sentiment, not the buying-to-cover, that sustained the we=
eks-long price appreciation of GameStop stock.Here is Figure 6:There was de=
finitely some short-covering, but what this picture mostly shows is that wh=
en the dotted line (price) skyrockets the red bars (short-covering) flatten=
. The story is not so much that retail investors on Reddit identified a sto=
ck that was over-shorted, bid up the price, and thus forced all the short s=
ellers to cover their shorts at new highs and push up the price more. The s=
tory is more that the retail investors bid up the price, the short sellers =
covered and pushed up the price a bit more, and then the retail investors =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0possibly influenced by rumors of a short squeeze, or by shor=
t interest figures being reported on a lag =E2=80=94=C2=A0went and pushed u=
p the price much, much more. And the short sellers had either covered befor=
e that happened, or said =E2=80=9Cwell this price is ridiculous=E2=80=9D an=
d waited to cover until it fell.=C2=A0Actually the SEC almost concludes tha=
t there should have been=C2=A0more=C2=A0short selling:The price surge in GM=
E also raises questions of market efficiency that relate to short selling. =
Staff have observed that it was unusually costly to borrow shares in GME.=
=C2=A0Academic research implicates constraints on short selling as a possib=
le contributor to bubbles where stock prices rise above what may be justifi=
ed by fundamentals. Such constraints on short selling could arise from cost=
 or from risk aversion. To the extent that GameStop was costly and risky to=
 short, the reluctance to sell short could have contributed to the run-up i=
n prices and the subsequent steep decline.Did GameStop rocket because of a =
gamma squeeze? That is: Did retail traders buy a ton of call options, forci=
ng options market makers to hedge by buying a ton of stock and then buy mor=
e as the stock rose?[2]=C2=A0No, not at all, says the SEC:Staff did not fin=
d evidence of a gamma squeeze in GME during January 2021. One of the main d=
rivers of a gamma squeeze is an influx of call option purchases, which caus=
es market makers to hedge their writing of the call options by purchasing t=
he underlying stock, driving up the stock price in the process. While staff=
 did find GME options trading volume from individual customers increased su=
bstantially, from only $58.5 million on January 21 to $563.4 million on Jan=
uary 22 until peaking at $2.4 billion on January 27, this increase in optio=
ns trading volume was mostly driven by an increase in the buying of put, ra=
ther than call, options. Further, data show that market-makers were buying,=
 rather than writing, call options. These observations by themselves are no=
t consistent with a gamma squeeze.That=E2=80=99s sort of a weird result. =
=E2=80=9CMarket-makers were buying, rather than writing, call options=E2=80=
=9D means that customers were=C2=A0selling=C2=A0call options on GameStop. O=
ne possible interpretation of that is that retail investors were in fact bu=
ying call options to=C2=A0bet=C2=A0on GameStop =E2=80=94=C2=A0as they said =
they were on Reddit, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but hedge funds and institutions w=
ere=C2=A0selling=C2=A0call options as a way to get short GameStop, and the =
hedge-fund sales outweighed the retail buys. (And in fact  there are storie=
s about hedge funds selling GameStop=C2=A0calls at the peak and making a to=
n of money.) Meanwhile though retail was mostly buying puts=C2=A0during Gam=
eStop=E2=80=99s big week, also betting that the stock would go down (or hed=
ging the gains they had made). And the SEC says elsewhere that =E2=80=9Cbet=
ween January 22 and January 27, GME traders began to suddenly close their c=
all option positions.=E2=80=9D All of this =E2=80=94=C2=A0market makers sel=
ling puts and buying calls =E2=80=94=C2=A0would tend to have the effect of =
pushing the stock=C2=A0down, as the market makers hedged both sold puts and=
 bought calls by selling GameStop stock.[3] Retail traders YOLOing short-da=
ted out-of-the-money call options does not seem to explain much of what hap=
pened in GameStop=E2=80=99s big week.What else? Did GameStop eventually cra=
sh late in that week because Robinhood limited its customers=E2=80=99 abili=
ty to buy the stock? Maybe, why not, though the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t really =
take a position. But did Robinhood impose limits because of some evil consp=
iracy with hedge funds and market makers? No, of course not; Robinhood (and=
 other brokers) imposed limits on GameStop (and other meme stock) trading b=
ecause of margin requirements at their clearinghouses.The way  stock tradin=
g works is that a buyer and seller agree to a trade on the stock exchange a=
nd then, two days later, the buyer delivers the money and the seller delive=
rs the shares. That creates two days of credit risk: If the buyer vanishes,=
 the seller doesn=E2=80=99t get paid. To solve this, there are clearinghous=
es that essentially guarantee every trade; if you sell stock, you can be co=
nfident that you=E2=80=99ll get=C2=A0your money in two days, because the cl=
earinghouse will pay you. The main stock clearinghouse is the National Secu=
rities Clearing Corp. (NSCC); the main options one is the Options Clearing =
Corp. (OCC). Brokers are required to keep cash at the clearinghouses to gua=
rantee their obligations to settle trades. The more trades a broker does, a=
nd the riskier those obligations are, the more cash the broker needs. When =
there=E2=80=99s a ton of trading=C2=A0in very volatile stocks, the clearing=
houses will call brokers for more money:Clearing agencies (i.e., NSCC and, =
to a lesser extent, OCC) played important roles duringthe January 2021 GME =
market events. The risk management mechanisms of these clearingagencies eff=
ectively led others in the transaction chain=E2=80=94such as retail broker-=
dealers=E2=80=94to pauseand manage the risk exposure that arose as the rate=
 of transactions accelerated. Both NSCC andOCC experienced record volumes c=
leared on January 27, 2021.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6In highly volatile trading where =
share prices whipsaw by hundreds of dollars, NSCC may require more margin t=
o guard against an increased risk of defaults (which may occur if, for exam=
ple, buyers do not carry-through on paying for a stock that has plummeted o=
r sellers do not carry-through on delivering a stock that has skyrocketed).=
 On January 27, 2021, in response to market activity during the trading ses=
sion, NSCC made intraday margin calls from 36 clearing members totaling $6.=
9 billion, bringing the total required margin across all members to $25.5 b=
illion. Of the $6.9 billion, $2.1 billion were intraday mark-to-market call=
s, while the remaining $4.8 billion was a special ECP charge. Specifically,=
 NSCC observed unusual volatility in certain securities, including GME, whi=
ch presented heightened risk to the clearinghouse and its members.86 As a r=
esult, it calculated and assessed against certain affected members the rema=
ining $4.8 billion as an additional special charge pursuant to its establis=
hed rules. NSCC imposed this charge on 18 members, all of whom provided the=
 additional margin. NSCC subjected one additional member to the special cha=
rge, but that member ultimately did not have to meet that charge after offs=
etting its exposure with a transfer from an affiliate.Again, this is not a =
weird conspiracy but a normal operation of standard market structure.[4] Wh=
en trading goes haywire, there are rules to make sure that traders can cove=
r their obligations, and one way that those rules work is by effectively ca=
lming down the trading.What else. =E2=80=9CPayment for order flow.=E2=80=9D=
 The GameStop saga drew a lot of attention to the fact that retail brokers =
like Robinhood sell a lot of their customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0orders to =E2=80=
=9Coff-exchange market makers=E2=80=9D like Citadel Securities. We have  ta=
lked about that=C2=A0a lot before, the SEC explains it in a sober and strai=
ghtforward way,[5] and there doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have been anything par=
ticularly nefarious going on in that relationship. Still this is an interes=
ting little fact:GME trading in January 2021 shifted the prevailing distrib=
ution of GME equity executions across venues. Specifically, the proportion =
of off-exchange activity initially rose as individual investor activity inc=
reased, then fell as volatility increased. Approximately half of GME=E2=80=
=99s dollar and share volume reported to the consolidated tape in 2020 was =
executed on a national securities exchange. On January 21, 2021 (when GME o=
pened at $39.23 and closed at $43.03), 62.60% of the day=E2=80=99s dollar v=
olume was executed off exchange. But, beginning on January 22 (when GME ope=
ned at $42.59 and closed at $65.01), the percentage of dollar volume execut=
ed off exchange consistently dipped below 50%, reaching a low of 32.83% on =
January 28 (when GME opened at $265.00 and closed at $193.60).An increasing=
 percentage of volume executed on exchange when volatility spikes may indic=
ate that market participants, including wholesalers, are seeking to avoid i=
nternalizing customer orders to reduce potential losses when hedging become=
s more difficult.The first part of the story is that, stereotypically, inst=
itutional trading often happens on exchanges but retail trading normally ha=
ppens off-exchange, with wholesalers (market makers). As retail piled into =
GameStop, more of its trading happened off exchanges.But the second part of=
 the story is that in fact those market makers=C2=A0can=C2=A0just send the =
retail orders on to exchanges, rather than trading with them themselves.[6]=
 Often they prefer not to do this, because in general it is profitable to t=
rade with those retail orders. But as things got absolutely wild in GameSto=
p, the market makers seem often to have said =E2=80=9Cmeh we don=E2=80=99t =
need this aggravation=E2=80=9D and sent the orders out to exchanges.[7] In =
general, if you buy stock through a retail brokerage, you=E2=80=99re not bu=
ying it on the exchange, you're buying it from a wholesaler. But enough peo=
ple bought GameStop in the last week of January to break that system; they =
ended up buying a lot of their stock on the exchange.=C2=A0The report ends =
with a shrug in the direction of market reforms that SEC Chair Gary Gensler=
  wants to do anyway: reducing=C2=A0settlement times to reduce clearinghous=
e risk, improved reporting of short sales, more transparency for off-exchan=
ge trading. None of these things have much to do with what happened to Game=
Stop that last week in January. Or here=E2=80=99s this:Consideration should=
 be given to whether game-like features and celebratory animations that are=
 likely intended to create positive feedback from trading lead investors to=
 trade more than they would otherwise. In addition, payment for order flow =
and the incentives it creates may cause broker-dealers to find novel ways t=
o increase customer trading, including through the use of digital engagemen=
t practices.Yeah, look.=C2=A0In general, do retail brokerages have economic=
 incentives to push more trading? Yes, definitely. Do little animations of =
confetti to celebrate a trade make people more likely to trade? Sure, maybe=
, why not.=C2=A0Did people buy tons and tons of GameStop in the last week o=
f January because of the game-like user experience of their brokerage apps?=
=C2=A0No, of course not, come on. The game of GameStop, in January 2021, wa=
s not about getting to the top of Robinhood=E2=80=99s leader board or whate=
ver. (Robinhood was trying to=C2=A0stop=C2=A0people from trading GameStop t=
hat week! It actually=C2=A0prevented=C2=A0them from buying GameStop for a w=
hile!) The game of GameStop was pervasive in society; if you were buying Ga=
meStop stock it was because you read about it on Reddit or on the front pag=
e of every newspaper, or because you heard about it on every television new=
s show. There were at least eight GameStop film projects in the works by mi=
d-February! =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s all buy GameStop and get rich=E2=80=9D w=
as absolutely a weird game-like positive feedback loop that led investors t=
o trade more than they would otherwise, but Robinhood=E2=80=99s app design =
had nothing to do with it.So the SEC=E2=80=99s report doesn=E2=80=99t so mu=
ch explain=C2=A0what happened to GameStop; really it just=C2=A0rules out=C2=
=A0various popular, technical-ish, conspiracy-ish explanations. =E2=80=9CYo=
u see, GameStop=E2=80=99s stock went up 2,700% in January[8] on no news bec=
ause of this complex equation involving gamma, retail options volume, short=
 positioning and sunspots=E2=80=9D is a good explanation in that (1) it exp=
lains a weird thing in a weird way and (2)=C2=A0reading it makes you feel s=
mart and in-the-know. But, the SEC says =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I think they=E2=
=80=99re probably right =E2=80=94=C2=A0it isn=E2=80=99t true.=E2=80=9CYou s=
ee, GameStop=E2=80=99s stock went up 2,700% in January on no news because a=
 bunch of small retail investors simultaneously decided to buy it=E2=80=9D =
is a bad explanation in that it explains a wild phenomenon in a boring way,=
 and in that it doesn=E2=80=99t tell you anything=C2=A0useful. There is no =
technical fix to market structure that would prevent that sort of thing fro=
m happening, nor is it obvious that you=E2=80=99d want to prevent that sort=
 of thing (people all deciding to buy a stock) from happening. There is=C2=
=A0no obvious set of technical indicators that would help you identify futu=
re whatever-this-is situations;=C2=A0options positioning and short interest=
 and whatever seem to have been less important than just everyone in the wo=
rld liking the stock at the same time.=C2=A0One other thing that might be w=
orth mentioning is that the volume-weighted average price of GameStop stock=
 during its crazy last week of January=C2=A0was $166.23.[9] It closed yeste=
rday at $186.02. If you bought GameStop during its insane week, you=E2=80=
=99re probably up. If your explanation of GameStop is =E2=80=9Cweird techni=
cal stuff happened that week and the price went crazy,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Cevil conspiracies happened that week and the price went crazy,=E2=80=9D =
or even just =E2=80=9Cwe all collectively lost our minds that week and the =
price went crazy,=E2=80=9D how do you explain that =E2=80=94=C2=A0with less=
 attention and less volatility and less weird technical stuff =E2=80=94 it=
=E2=80=99s still happening?
