A couple of years ago Elon Musk was going around getting  fined millions of=
 dollars by the SEC and sued by a cave diver for being on Twitter too much,=
 and I was  writing dumb columns that were like =E2=80=9Cmaybe Elon Musk sh=
ould focus on building cars=C2=A0and spend less time getting in legal troub=
le on Twitter.=E2=80=9D I mean to be fair also the SEC and a federal judge =
and Tesla Inc.=E2=80=99s=C2=A0 Designated Counsel for Keeping Musk Off Twit=
ter were also saying =E2=80=9CElon, get off Twitter, man.=E2=80=9D And at l=
east the SEC had a point; he was doing a certain amount of securities fraud=
 on Twitter and their job is to stop that. But as a matter of=C2=A0corporat=
e finance=C2=A0Musk was clearly right and I, at least, was wrong. Given the=
 choice of spending an hour designing a bumper for a car or spending an hou=
r tweeting memes, Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0who is not particularly an engineer b=
ut who is huge on=C2=A0Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0clearly should almost always =
choose Twitter. Being much too online has gotten Musk a rabid fan base, and=
 they=E2=80=99re investors, and that allows Tesla=C2=A0to raise limitless a=
mounts of money for Tesla at an attractive cost of capital, and also frankl=
y lets it make spare cash on Bitcoin speculation if it wants to. A Musk twe=
et is a ludicrously, implausibly=C2=A0valuable=C2=A0thing in a way that a M=
usk-designed windshield wiper probably isn=E2=80=99t. If he can make a twee=
t worth tens of millions of dollars with a minute=E2=80=99s effort he proba=
bly should just do that, instead of expending more effort to make something=
 less valuable.Similarly  here=E2=80=99s Adam Aron:AMC Entertainment Holdin=
gs Inc., is a favorite of meme-stock investors and Chief Executive Officer =
Adam Aron finds out what they -- and movie goers -- think by posting messag=
es on Twitter almost every day and reading most of the comments he gets in =
return.=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s very helpful for me running an organization to=
 know what my constituency cares about,=E2=80=9D Aron said Monday on a pane=
l at the Milken Institute Global Conference in Beverly Hills, California. =
=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a lot of learning that can go on, if you not only =
speak on Twitter, but you read what people are speaking back to you.=E2=80=
=9DLearning, I don=E2=80=99t know, sure, but the guy has raised umpteen bil=
lion dollars and gotten his=C2=A0movie-theater company=C2=A0through a=C2=A0=
global pandemic=C2=A0in much better financial shape than it was before the =
pandemic by going all-in on embracing his meme-stock status. And, yes, that=
 requires being down to clown on social media.=C2=A0There is a traditional =
view of corporate social media in which a board would tell its chief execut=
ive officer to be cautious and anodyne on Twitter. There are many things th=
at can go wrong with an unhinged Twitter presence, and not a lot that can g=
o right, is what your lawyer would probably tell you. But the last few year=
s have altered that calculation, and now the things that can go right are l=
ike =E2=80=9Craising billions of dollars of retail capital when you need it=
 most,=C2=A0at all-time-high valuations.=E2=80=9D Arguably=C2=A0it=E2=80=99=
s a breach of fiduciary duties=C2=A0not=C2=A0to be weird on Twitter all the=
 time.
