<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">GameStop report!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday the=C2=A0U.S. Securities and=
 Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAy=
MS0yMTI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe30680c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">released</a> a =E2=80=9C=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9zdGFmZi1yZXBvcnQtZXF1aXR5LW9wdGlvbnMtbWFya=
2V0LXN0cnVjdGlvbi1jb25kaXRpb25zLWVhcmx5LTIwMjEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB34ee8f95" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">Staff Report on Equity and Options Market Structure Con=
ditions in Early 2021</a>,=E2=80=9D specifically the conditions that allowe=
d GameStop Corp.=E2=80=99s stock to go from $17.25 to $325 over the course =
of January for no particular reason. It would have been cool if the SEC had=
, uh, found a reason. If the report was like =E2=80=9Cactually we looked de=
ep into the stock exchange=E2=80=99s computers and found that they accident=
ally shifted a decimal point one spot to the right, that was supposed to be=
 $32.50, oops,=E2=80=9D that would have been an interesting result.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or at the time this was all happening, there were =
a lot of theories about =E2=80=9Cshort squeezes=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgamma=
 squeezes=E2=80=9D and nefarious hedge funds doing evil things to manipulat=
e=C2=A0the stock. If the SEC had said =E2=80=9Cit was gamma, just so much g=
amma,=E2=80=9D that would have added to our understanding of the world. Or =
if it had said =E2=80=9Cactually some big hedge funds=C2=A0were hugely <em>=
long</em> GameStop and manipulated the price up behind the scenes by doing =
wash trades with their=C2=A0cronies,=E2=80=9D that would have been really c=
ool and fun.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But instead the SEC repo=
rt =E2=80=94=C2=A0look,=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s not a=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>repo=
rt. If the GameStop saga got you interested in market structure, if you rea=
d a few GameStop articles and started thinking things like =E2=80=9Cwait ho=
w can more than 100% of the stock be sold short=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy wo=
uld Citadel Securities pay Robinhood to trade with=C2=A0its customers=E2=80=
=99 orders=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhat is a gamma squeeze,=E2=80=9D then the =
SEC report is a crisp, sober, sensible, useful and readable explainer. It=
=E2=80=99s fine! But if you spent the week of GameStop immersed in GameStop=
 then there is nothing all that new here. It=E2=80=99s a little boring. =E2=
=80=9CMany observers anticipated much more,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1l=
cy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMC8xOS9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9nYW1lc3RvcC1tZW1lLXN0b2Nrcy1=
yZXBvcnQuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e5f65f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says DealBook</a=
>. GameStop was so big, and so weird! This one stock going up a lot dominat=
ed the national news for like a week. It cries out for a correspondingly bi=
g and weird explanation. But, nah. People just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0liked the sto=
ck?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So: Did GameStop rocket up because of a=
 short squeeze?[1] Yes, a bit,=C2=A0the SEC says, but in fact the short sel=
lers who threw in the towel and bought in their GameStop shorts were only a=
 small percentage of volume, and they mostly did so=C2=A0<em>early=C2=A0</e=
m>in GameStop=E2=80=99s big run in the last week of January:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Staff observed that during some discrete peri=
ods, GME had sharp price increases concurrently with known major short sell=
ers covering their short positions after incurring significant losses. Duri=
ng these times, short sellers covering their positions likely contributed t=
o increases in GME=E2=80=99s price.=C2=A0For example, staff observed that=
=C2=A0particularly during the earlier rise from January 22 to 27 the price =
of GME rose as the short interest decreased. Staff also observed discrete p=
eriods of sharp price increases during which accounts held by firms known t=
o the staff to be covering short interest in GME were actively buying large=
 volumes of GME shares, in some cases accounting for very significant porti=
ons of the net buying pressure during a period. Figure 6 shows that buy vol=
ume in GME, including buy volume from participants identified as having lar=
ge short positions, increased significantly beginning around January 22 and=
 remained high for several days, corresponding to the beginning of the most=
 dramatic phase of the run-up in GME=E2=80=99s price.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Figure 6 shows that the run-up in GME stock price coincided with=
 buying by those with short positions. However, it also shows that such buy=
ing was a small fraction of overall buy volume, and that GME share prices c=
ontinued to be high after the direct effects of covering short positions wo=
uld have waned. The underlying motivation of such buy volume cannot be dete=
rmined; perhaps it was motivated by the desire to maintain a short squeeze.=
 Whether driven by a desire to squeeze short sellers and thus to profit fro=
m the resultant rise in price, or by belief in the fundamentals of GameStop=
, it was the positive sentiment, not the buying-to-cover, that sustained th=
e weeks-long price appreciation of GameStop stock.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is Figure 6:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iYYPmqH.ib.s/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/iYYPmqH.ib.s/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was definitely some short-co=
vering, but what this picture mostly shows is that when the dotted line (pr=
ice) skyrockets the red bars (short-covering) flatten. The story is not so =
much that retail investors on Reddit identified a stock that was over-short=
ed, bid up the price, and thus forced all the short sellers to cover their =
shorts at new highs and push up the price more. The story is more that the =
retail investors bid up the price, the short sellers covered and pushed up =
the price a bit more, and then the retail investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0possibly=
 influenced by rumors of a short squeeze, or by short interest figures bein=
g reported on a lag =E2=80=94=C2=A0went and pushed up the price much, much =
more. And the short sellers had either covered before that happened, or sai=
d =E2=80=9Cwell this price is ridiculous=E2=80=9D and waited to cover until=
 it fell.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually the SEC almost con=
cludes that there should have been=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>short selling:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The price surge in GME also rais=
es questions of market efficiency that relate to short selling. Staff have =
observed that it was unusually costly to borrow shares in GME.=C2=A0Academi=
c research implicates constraints on short selling as a possible contributo=
r to bubbles where stock prices rise above what may be justified by fundame=
ntals. Such constraints on short selling could arise from cost or from risk=
 aversion. To the extent that GameStop was costly and risky to short, the r=
eluctance to sell short could have contributed to the run-up in prices and =
the subsequent steep decline.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Did GameStop rocket because of a gamma squeeze? That is: Did retail traders=
 buy a ton of call options, forcing options market makers to hedge by buyin=
g a ton of stock and then buy more as the stock rose?[2]=C2=A0No, not at al=
l, says the SEC:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Staff did not =
find evidence of a gamma squeeze in GME during January 2021. One of the mai=
n drivers of a gamma squeeze is an influx of call option purchases, which c=
auses market makers to hedge their writing of the call options by purchasin=
g the underlying stock, driving up the stock price in the process. While st=
aff did find GME options trading volume from individual customers increased=
 substantially, from only $58.5 million on January 21 to $563.4 million on =
January 22 until peaking at $2.4 billion on January 27, this increase in op=
tions trading volume was mostly driven by an increase in the buying of put,=
 rather than call, options. Further, data show that market-makers were buyi=
ng, rather than writing, call options. These observations by themselves are=
 not consistent with a gamma squeeze.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">That=E2=80=99s sort of a weird result. =E2=80=9CMarket-makers were =
buying, rather than writing, call options=E2=80=9D means that customers wer=
e=C2=A0<em>selling=C2=A0</em>call options on GameStop. One possible interpr=
etation of that is that retail investors were in fact buying call options t=
o=C2=A0bet=C2=A0on GameStop =E2=80=94=C2=A0as they said they were on Reddit=
, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but hedge funds and institutions were=C2=A0<em>sellin=
g=C2=A0</em>call options as a way to get short GameStop, and the hedge-fund=
 sales outweighed the retail buys. (And in fact <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1=
cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJ=
