ing particularly nefarious going on in that relationship. Still this is an =
interesting little fact:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GME tr=
ading in January 2021 shifted the prevailing distribution of GME equity exe=
cutions across venues. Specifically, the proportion of off-exchange activit=
y initially rose as individual investor activity increased, then fell as vo=
latility increased. Approximately half of GME=E2=80=99s dollar and share vo=
lume reported to the consolidated tape in 2020 was executed on a national s=
ecurities exchange. On January 21, 2021 (when GME opened at $39.23 and clos=
ed at $43.03), 62.60% of the day=E2=80=99s dollar volume was executed off e=
xchange. But, beginning on January 22 (when GME opened at $42.59 and closed=
 at $65.01), the percentage of dollar volume executed off exchange consiste=
ntly dipped below 50%, reaching a low of 32.83% on January 28 (when GME ope=
ned at $265.00 and closed at $193.60).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An i=
ncreasing percentage of volume executed on exchange when volatility spikes =
may indicate that market participants, including wholesalers, are seeking t=
o avoid internalizing customer orders to reduce potential losses when hedgi=
ng becomes more difficult.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 first part of the story is that, stereotypically, institutional trading of=
ten happens on exchanges but retail trading normally happens off-exchange, =
with wholesalers (market makers). As retail piled into GameStop, more of it=
s trading happened off exchanges.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the s=
econd part of the story is that in fact those market makers=C2=A0<em>can=C2=
=A0</em>just send the retail orders on to exchanges, rather than trading wi=
th them themselves.[6] Often they prefer not to do this, because in general=
 it is profitable to trade with those retail orders. But as things got abso=
lutely wild in GameStop, the market makers seem often to have said =E2=80=
=9Cmeh we don=E2=80=99t need this aggravation=E2=80=9D and sent the orders =
out to exchanges.[7] In general, if you buy stock through a retail brokerag=
e, you=E2=80=99re not buying it on the exchange, you're buying it from a wh=
olesaler. But enough people bought GameStop in the last week of January to =
break that system; they ended up buying a lot of their stock on the exchang=
e.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The report ends with a shrug in th=
e direction of market reforms that SEC Chair Gary Gensler <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
