lid; background-color: #ccc;">reported</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Many investors are beginning to question the logic of paying e=
xtra for a bond with a =E2=80=9Cgreen=E2=80=9D label, arguing that there ar=
e better ways to incentivise sovereign or corporate borrowers to boost thei=
r spending on environmentally friendly projects.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">These fund managers say that companies or governments should be rewar=
ded =E2=80=94 or penalised =E2=80=94 based on their green efforts as a whol=
e, rather than hiving off a small part of their activities and rebadging th=
e debt used to pay for it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe alwa=
ys evaluate an issuer in its entirety, not just one bond,=E2=80=9D says Mad=
eleine King, co-head of global credit research at Legal &amp; General Inves=
tment Management. She argues that it makes little sense to pay a premium fo=
r a green bond compared with a normal bond from the same company when the c=
reditworthiness =E2=80=94 and the sustainability credentials =E2=80=94 of t=
he issuer are the same in either case.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Conversely, here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
