ose of the short interest calculation.=E2=80=9D Still another question migh=
t be: =E2=80=9CWas there a lot of evil naked shorting?=E2=80=9D Again the a=
nswer is no: =E2=80=9CThe unusually high amount of short selling raised the=
 question of whether some of the short sales were =E2=80=98naked=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=94namely, made without arranging to borrow the underlying security. =
When a naked short sale occurs, the seller fails to deliver the securities =
to the buyer, and staff did observe spikes in fails to deliver in GME. Howe=
ver, fails to deliver can occur either with short or long sales, making the=
m an imperfect measure of naked short selling. Moreover, based on the staff=
=E2=80=99s review of the available data, GME did not experience persistent =
fails to deliver at the individual clearing member level. Specifically, sta=
ff observed that most clearing members were able to clear any fails relativ=
ely quickly, i.e., within a few days, and for the most part did not experie=
nce fails across multiple days.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;"><em>[2] We discussed the mechanics in more detail <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxOTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMDE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB20fade04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the first time we talked about GameStop=
</a>, way back on Jan. 25.=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[=
3] The effect of the price moves on the hedges =E2=80=94=C2=A0the actual ga=
mma =E2=80=94 is more ambiguous. The way you hedge a bought call is by shor=
ting stock and then shorting more as the stock goes up (and the calls becom=
e more in-the-money). The way you hedge a sold put is by shorting stock and=
 then buying some back as the stock goes up (and the puts become more out-o=
f-the-money). So if market makers were buying calls and selling puts, their=
 initial hedging would push the stock down, but their dynamic hedging would=
 to some extent offset.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[4] In fac=
t, NSCC =E2=80=9Cexcess capital premium=E2=80=9D rules allowed it to call f=
or significantly *more* cash than it did, but it waived those calls to avoi=
d blowing up brokers too much.=C2=A0The SEC says: =E2=80=9CBecause these me=
mbers=E2=80=99 ratios of excess risk versus capital were not driven by indi=
vidual clearing member actions, but by extreme volatility in individual cle=
ared equities, NSCC exercised its rules-based discretion to waive the ECP c=
harge for all members on January 28, 2021. Absent this waiver, one retail b=
roker-dealer would have had an additional ECP charge of more than double it=
s margin requirement of $1.4 billion on January 28, 2021.=E2=80=9D <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25393723.275721/aHR0cHM6L=
y9kaWZmLnN1YnN0YWNrLmNvbS9wL2dhbWVzdG9wLXJlbWFpbnMtYS1teXN0ZXJ5/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBaefc2cf9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">Byrne Hobart writes</a>: =E2=80=9CSo the co=
nspiracy was to relax requirements for one broker-dealer, to the (marginal)=
 benefit of retail investors.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
><em>[5] Here=E2=80=99s its explanation of why market makers will pay for o=
rder flow, and how it gets retail customers better prices: =E2=80=9COff-exc=
hange market makers use segmentation to mitigate one of the key risks trade=
rs face=E2=80=94prices moving against their positions after executing a tra=
de. Some in the marketplace may possess superior information about underlyi=
ng asset values and will only buy when posted prices are low relative to th=
eir information, and sell when they are high. Other participants may, by vi=
rtue of greater quantities of data, have statistically greater predictive a=
bility regarding the direction of prices. Because market makers are more li=
kely to lose money when interacting with such order flow, they have an ince=
ntive to distinguish order flow that does not correlate with future price m=
ovements from order flow that does. The bid-ask spread, the difference betw=
een what a buyer is willing to pay and a seller willing to accept, normally=
 compensates market makers for the risk that prices may move against them.=
=C2=A0To the extent that market makers can segment order flow that is less =
correlated with future prices, they can offer a lower spread when trading w=
ith this order flow. Besides differing in the motive for trading, such orde=
rs are more likely to be small, uncorrelated with one another, and thus =E2=
=80=98one and done=E2=80=99 (i.e., not the first in a series of orders inte=
nded to transact a large amount of stock), which also allows for a tighter =
spread.=C2=A0Off-exchange market makers typically offer payment to the reta=
il broker-dealer for the right to trade with its customer order flow (i.e.,=
 payment for order flow).=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em=
>[6] The SEC says: =E2=80=9CFor stocks, off-exchange market makers may exec=
ute individual investor orders by taking the other side of the trade princi=
pally (=E2=80=98internalizing=E2=80=99=C2=A0the trade) or may route the ord=
er to other trading venues for execution.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;"><em>[7] This could be about short-term price risk =E2=80=94 =
=E2=80=9Cmeh, we don=E2=80=99t want to be on the wrong side of a tidal wave=
 of retail orders=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0or just about inventory risk =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe just sold a billion dollars of stock to retail, we =
can=E2=80=99t sell them anymore.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;"><em>[8] That is a somewhat non-canonical number that I took from =
the SEC report: =E2=80=9COverall, GME=E2=80=99s intraday share price increa=
sed approximately 2,700% from its intraday low on January 8 to its intraday=
 high on January 28, followed by a decrease of over 86% from that day to th=
e closing price at the end of the first week of February.=E2=80=9D</em></p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[9] That's Bloomberg page GME US &lt;Equit=
y&gt; AQR, from the morning of Jan. 25 to the evening of Jan. 29.=C2=A0</em=
></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[10] This is too crude, and there are=
 good general finance reasons that corporate-level financing might be cheap=
er or better (diversification of assets, financial flexibility, etc.) or co=
nversely that project-level financing might be cheaper or better (more seni=
or security on the assets, less recourse to other assets, etc.).=C2=A0</em>=
</p>
